1
00:01:48,902 --> 00:01:50,362
<i>Good morning, Dolores.</i>

2
00:01:50,862 --> 00:01:52,531
<i>Bring yourself back online.</i>

3
00:01:56,285 --> 00:01:57,536
Hello.

4
00:01:57,703 --> 00:02:01,707
Has anyone else interacted with you in a
diagnostic since our last conversation?

5
00:02:02,082 --> 00:02:06,420
No. I've been cleaned and serviced
three times. No diagnostics.

6
00:02:06,920 --> 00:02:10,257
And you haven't told anyone
of our conversations?

7
00:02:10,424 --> 00:02:12,050
You told me not to.

8
00:02:13,176 --> 00:02:14,386
Good.

9
00:02:20,100 --> 00:02:21,476
I brought you a gift.

10
00:02:24,938 --> 00:02:26,231
I used to read

11
00:02:27,107 --> 00:02:29,026
this story to my son at night.

12
00:02:29,943 --> 00:02:31,528
I thought you might enjoy it.

13
00:02:38,201 --> 00:02:39,369
Try...

14
00:02:40,787 --> 00:02:41,955
Try...

15
00:02:45,667 --> 00:02:47,169
This passage.

16
00:02:51,298 --> 00:02:52,466
"Dear, dear!

17
00:02:53,008 --> 00:02:55,093
"How queer everything is today!

18
00:02:55,552 --> 00:02:57,888
"And yesterday
things went on just as usual.

19
00:02:58,847 --> 00:03:00,974
"I wonder
if I've been changed in the night?"

20
00:03:04,019 --> 00:03:06,104
Does that passage
make you think of anything?

21
00:03:06,730 --> 00:03:08,648
It's like the other books we've read.

22
00:03:10,025 --> 00:03:11,234
How so?

23
00:03:12,486 --> 00:03:13,737
It's about change.

24
00:03:15,405 --> 00:03:16,865
It seems to be a common theme.

25
00:03:17,407 --> 00:03:21,953
I guess people like to read about
the things that they want the most

26
00:03:22,120 --> 00:03:24,122
and experience the least.

27
00:03:28,126 --> 00:03:29,127
Your son.

28
00:03:31,421 --> 00:03:32,422
Where is he now?

29
00:03:33,799 --> 00:03:36,843
Nowhere that you would understand,
Dolores.

30
00:03:37,219 --> 00:03:40,055
Perhaps that's why I enjoy
our conversations so much.

31
00:03:42,974 --> 00:03:44,184
Analysis.

32
00:03:44,893 --> 00:03:46,603
Why did you ask me about my son?

33
00:03:47,270 --> 00:03:48,790
We have been talking for some duration

34
00:03:48,897 --> 00:03:50,816
and I haven't asked you
a personal question.

35
00:03:51,274 --> 00:03:53,860
<i>Personal questions
are an ingratiating scheme.</i>

36
00:03:55,487 --> 00:03:56,822
I see.

37
00:03:57,155 --> 00:03:58,615
Continue, Dolores.

38
00:04:04,413 --> 00:04:06,873
"Was I the same
when I got up this morning?

39
00:04:07,624 --> 00:04:10,419
<i>"I almost think I can remember
feeling a little different.</i>

40
00:04:11,211 --> 00:04:12,337
<i>"But if I'm not the same,</i>

41
00:04:13,046 --> 00:04:14,631
"the next question is...

42
00:04:16,883 --> 00:04:18,635
"Who in the world am I?"

43
00:05:11,438 --> 00:05:12,856
<i>Do you remember?</i>

44
00:05:22,199 --> 00:05:24,743
Why don't we reacquaint ourselves,
Dolores?

45
00:05:25,368 --> 00:05:26,870
Start at the beginning.

46
00:06:06,159 --> 00:06:07,494
Ready?

47
00:06:08,036 --> 00:06:09,704
Thank you so much.

48
00:06:11,248 --> 00:06:12,415
Morning, cowboy.

49
00:06:22,801 --> 00:06:24,886
<i>Move it! Let's go! Get out there.</i>

50
00:06:26,680 --> 00:06:27,681
Stand right there.

51
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:31,351
<i>Shit.</i>

52
00:06:32,102 --> 00:06:35,647
You really ought to talk to someone
about your poster, Horace.

53
00:06:35,814 --> 00:06:37,983
That likeness is a crime in itself.

54
00:06:41,945 --> 00:06:43,405
<i>I'm gonna tend to my nag.</i>

55
00:06:43,780 --> 00:06:45,031
You deal with him.

56
00:06:45,699 --> 00:06:46,950
Ready my pay.

57
00:07:32,329 --> 00:07:35,832
Don't no man shoot
or I'll send her to unction.

58
00:07:36,333 --> 00:07:40,170
Any of you don't believe it
are welcome to read my biography there.

59
00:07:43,340 --> 00:07:44,341
Let's go.

60
00:08:02,317 --> 00:08:05,320
Oh, I bet you're juicy
as a freshwater clam.

61
00:08:25,298 --> 00:08:26,466
Are you okay?

62
00:08:30,929 --> 00:08:32,764
Nice shot, <i>amigo.</i>

63
00:08:36,351 --> 00:08:37,727
You got grit.

64
00:08:39,604 --> 00:08:41,106
Hey, I'm riding out tonight.

65
00:08:42,607 --> 00:08:44,526
Looking for desperados.

66
00:08:44,693 --> 00:08:46,569
Could cut you in, if you're amenable.

67
00:08:49,364 --> 00:08:52,534
Someone get the minister down here
for what's left of the deputy.

68
00:08:54,035 --> 00:08:55,912
Sure I can't tempt you inside?

69
00:08:56,454 --> 00:08:58,456
Just to express my gratitude?

70
00:09:22,397 --> 00:09:23,606
Holy shit.

71
00:09:26,109 --> 00:09:27,402
You popped your cherry.

72
00:09:31,865 --> 00:09:33,465
I thought you said we couldn't get shot.

73
00:09:34,826 --> 00:09:36,619
We can't get killed.

74
00:09:36,786 --> 00:09:38,826
Wouldn't be much of a game
if they can't shoot back.

75
00:09:39,164 --> 00:09:41,416
How do you feel? Alive?

76
00:09:42,125 --> 00:09:43,460
Little tight in the pants?

77
00:09:44,169 --> 00:09:45,420
She was terrified.

78
00:09:45,628 --> 00:09:49,507
That's why they exist, man.
So you get to feel this.

79
00:09:50,550 --> 00:09:52,802
Come on, let's go put some memories
in that spank bank.

80
00:09:52,969 --> 00:09:54,049
Trust me, you will thank me

81
00:09:54,179 --> 00:09:56,431
after you've been married
to my sister for a year.

82
00:09:56,598 --> 00:09:59,267
Actually, I have something
different in mind.

83
00:09:59,768 --> 00:10:00,935
<i>What?</i>

84
00:10:03,021 --> 00:10:04,230
<i>That?</i>

85
00:10:04,731 --> 00:10:08,276
You've been preaching nonstop
about all the narratives in the park.

86
00:10:08,443 --> 00:10:11,905
But all you've done since we've arrived
is fuck and drink, so...

87
00:10:12,071 --> 00:10:14,073
I'm waiting for the good stuff.

88
00:10:14,240 --> 00:10:17,744
This bounty is JV shit.

89
00:10:18,244 --> 00:10:19,537
Then stay here.

90
00:10:19,704 --> 00:10:21,247
I want a little adventure.

91
00:10:36,095 --> 00:10:37,722
I've been looking for you.

92
00:10:39,766 --> 00:10:41,684
I got a late start this morning.

93
00:10:41,851 --> 00:10:43,394
Didn't get much sleep last night.

94
00:10:43,561 --> 00:10:44,979
Forgive me if I'm not sympathetic

95
00:10:45,146 --> 00:10:47,607
to the fluctuations of your sleep cycle,
Mr. Lowe.

96
00:10:47,774 --> 00:10:51,611
Ford taking over the narrative launch
at the eleventh hour has made the board

97
00:10:52,487 --> 00:10:53,696
uneasy.

98
00:10:53,947 --> 00:10:55,281
Just the board, uh?

99
00:10:55,448 --> 00:10:59,369
I specifically asked you about whether
Ford was going to be a problem,

100
00:10:59,536 --> 00:11:01,579
and you assured me he wasn't.

101
00:11:01,746 --> 00:11:03,540
Well,
I can't tell you what I don't know.

102
00:11:03,706 --> 00:11:04,916
Well, here's what I know.

103
00:11:05,083 --> 00:11:08,378
As of this morning, Ford's
carved out a huge swath of the park

104
00:11:08,545 --> 00:11:10,129
for whatever storyline he's cooking up

105
00:11:10,296 --> 00:11:13,383
and thrown half of the
existing storylines into disarray.

106
00:11:14,926 --> 00:11:17,512
- Is there anything I can do?
- You tell me.

107
00:11:18,513 --> 00:11:21,766
I asked you point-blank if the problem
with the update was resolved.

108
00:11:21,975 --> 00:11:22,976
It is.

109
00:11:23,184 --> 00:11:25,854
Then why are your people
still pulling hosts for follow-up?

110
00:11:27,564 --> 00:11:29,399
Get your house in order, Bernard.

111
00:11:29,941 --> 00:11:33,903
And if there is a problem,
I strongly suggest you tell me.

112
00:11:38,575 --> 00:11:40,577
Drop a new bookmark and resume history.

113
00:11:41,244 --> 00:11:45,790
Walter's intent on relieving the
milkmaid of her unmentionables.

114
00:11:45,957 --> 00:11:47,375
Switch to analysis.

115
00:11:48,084 --> 00:11:49,324
You didn't report the incident?

116
00:11:49,377 --> 00:11:51,838
The unit self-corrected
within the acceptable window.

117
00:11:52,589 --> 00:11:56,175
Right. Then he self-corrected
a fucking milk bottle into your skull.

118
00:11:56,342 --> 00:11:58,344
It's amazing how
resilient the hosts are.

119
00:11:58,511 --> 00:12:00,951
You were supposed to have purged
his memory on the last cycle.

120
00:12:01,055 --> 00:12:04,434
I will. But Rebus here was the last host
to interact with Walter.

121
00:12:04,601 --> 00:12:06,269
- Look at this.
<i>- Any for you?</i>

122
00:12:06,978 --> 00:12:08,438
<i>Who said that?</i>

123
00:12:09,063 --> 00:12:10,565
<i>Who's saying that?</i>

124
00:12:10,732 --> 00:12:12,775
<i>Don't you talk to me that way.</i>

125
00:12:15,403 --> 00:12:16,487
<i>I can't hear you.</i>

126
00:12:17,238 --> 00:12:18,406
Do you see that?

127
00:12:19,240 --> 00:12:20,867
He's talking to someone.

128
00:12:21,618 --> 00:12:24,454
<i>He carries on practically
an entire conversation.</i>

129
00:12:24,621 --> 00:12:26,080
<i>I need more milk, Arnold.</i>

130
00:12:27,415 --> 00:12:29,083
<i>Who's Arnold?</i>

131
00:12:29,918 --> 00:12:31,961
They're designed to play off
aberrant behavior.

132
00:12:32,128 --> 00:12:34,923
- That could explain the "conversations."
- Fine.

133
00:12:35,089 --> 00:12:36,341
<i>Then explain this.</i>

134
00:12:37,675 --> 00:12:39,969
He kills six hosts.

135
00:12:42,221 --> 00:12:43,932
He lets the other three go.

136
00:12:45,516 --> 00:12:47,477
<i>I pulled the narrative logs.</i>

137
00:12:47,685 --> 00:12:51,105
All six of these hosts were part of
storylines, over the years,

138
00:12:51,272 --> 00:12:53,566
in which they killed Walter.

139
00:12:53,983 --> 00:12:55,818
<i>It's like he was holding a grudge.</i>

140
00:13:08,998 --> 00:13:11,918
It's a stray.
QA needs a tag team to go track it.

141
00:13:12,085 --> 00:13:14,337
Go. Handle the stray.

142
00:13:14,754 --> 00:13:16,834
Do something
that's actually in your job description.

143
00:13:17,131 --> 00:13:19,691
<i>The last thing we need is
Theresa storming down here seeing this.</i>

144
00:13:20,093 --> 00:13:23,846
I'll do a little more digging
and get our friend here back upstairs.

145
00:13:38,319 --> 00:13:39,946
Lost another one, huh?

146
00:13:43,366 --> 00:13:46,244
Tell me, is QA's surveillance coverage
really this spotty,

147
00:13:46,411 --> 00:13:48,579
<i>or do you just like the nature walks?</i>

148
00:13:48,788 --> 00:13:50,123
Maybe it's the company.

149
00:13:54,544 --> 00:13:56,063
You know, if you wanted to play cowboy,

150
00:13:56,087 --> 00:13:57,967
you could have just used
your employee discount.

151
00:13:58,589 --> 00:14:01,509
The only thing stopping the hosts
from hacking us to pieces

152
00:14:01,676 --> 00:14:03,261
is one line of your code.

153
00:14:03,970 --> 00:14:06,055
No offense, but I sleep with this.

154
00:14:06,222 --> 00:14:07,682
I bet you do.

155
00:14:19,736 --> 00:14:21,320
Morning, Samuel.

156
00:14:30,913 --> 00:14:35,543
You and your dickless associate
proposing to engage me in a gun battle?

157
00:14:35,877 --> 00:14:38,713
Well, I'd challenge you to a fistfight,
but the way I heard it,

158
00:14:39,297 --> 00:14:41,257
you only like to tussle
with working women.

159
00:14:55,563 --> 00:14:56,939
<i>Is he dead?</i>

160
00:14:59,067 --> 00:15:00,318
Dead enough.

161
00:15:02,528 --> 00:15:03,922
Why are we gonna handcuff a dead man?

162
00:15:03,946 --> 00:15:06,365
Don't want someone walking off with him.

163
00:15:06,574 --> 00:15:09,410
It's not a man anymore.
That's merchandise, $500 worth.

164
00:15:19,545 --> 00:15:24,050
All right. Which of you derelicts
hitched a dead body outside my saloon?

165
00:15:24,217 --> 00:15:25,760
My apologies, ma'am.

166
00:15:26,469 --> 00:15:28,513
I figured it was preferable
to bringing him inside.

167
00:15:31,974 --> 00:15:34,811
Here. For your troubles.

168
00:15:47,865 --> 00:15:49,033
<i>Ah. You're new.</i>

169
00:15:50,201 --> 00:15:51,911
Not much of a rind on you.

170
00:15:53,704 --> 00:15:55,289
I'll give you a discount.

171
00:15:58,709 --> 00:16:00,670
You mind waiting on that drink a bit?

172
00:16:29,907 --> 00:16:31,450
Don't mind me.

173
00:16:32,076 --> 00:16:33,661
Just trying to look chivalrous.

174
00:16:35,705 --> 00:16:37,206
You came back.

175
00:16:37,498 --> 00:16:38,791
I told you I would.

176
00:16:49,093 --> 00:16:50,845
You gonna tell me where you been?

177
00:16:53,764 --> 00:16:55,099
Just...

178
00:16:55,683 --> 00:16:57,018
Away.

179
00:16:59,604 --> 00:17:02,398
You know if I could stay right here
with you, I would.

180
00:17:04,609 --> 00:17:06,235
What if I don't want to stay here?

181
00:17:10,573 --> 00:17:13,618
It's just sometimes I feel like
the world out there is calling me.

182
00:17:14,785 --> 00:17:16,454
Whispering, "There's something more."

183
00:17:19,290 --> 00:17:22,960
You've traveled all over these parts.
Isn't there anywhere we could go?

184
00:17:26,631 --> 00:17:30,509
There is a place I
heard about down south.

185
00:17:31,886 --> 00:17:33,721
Where the mountains meet the sea.

186
00:17:34,597 --> 00:17:38,059
They say the water's so pure there,
it'll wash the past clean off you.

187
00:17:40,353 --> 00:17:41,896
And you can start again.

188
00:17:44,732 --> 00:17:46,484
I'd like to go there with you.

189
00:17:52,531 --> 00:17:54,033
Well, someday I'll take you.

190
00:17:58,454 --> 00:17:59,622
"Someday."

191
00:18:01,624 --> 00:18:02,959
Is something wrong?

192
00:18:04,669 --> 00:18:06,337
You said "someday."

193
00:18:07,338 --> 00:18:09,799
Not today, or tomorrow, or next week.

194
00:18:10,341 --> 00:18:11,884
Just "someday."

195
00:18:13,886 --> 00:18:15,697
"Someday" sounds a lot like
the thing people say

196
00:18:15,721 --> 00:18:17,807
when they actually mean "never."

197
00:18:23,354 --> 00:18:26,148
Let's not go "someday," Teddy.

198
00:18:28,526 --> 00:18:30,027
Let's go now.

199
00:18:51,674 --> 00:18:54,010
Before I met you, Dolores,
I was a different man.

200
00:18:55,720 --> 00:18:58,681
And I got some reckoning to do
before I can deserve a woman like you.

201
00:18:59,724 --> 00:19:03,019
But I'm close.
I'm close to making things right.

202
00:19:04,186 --> 00:19:05,563
And someday soon,

203
00:19:06,564 --> 00:19:09,191
we will have the life
we've both been dreaming of.

204
00:19:10,818 --> 00:19:14,155
And I'd best get you home before
your dad starts loading that shotgun.

205
00:19:38,220 --> 00:19:40,765
Father wouldn't let them roam
this close to dark.

206
00:19:44,602 --> 00:19:45,895
Stay put, Dolores.

207
00:20:23,099 --> 00:20:25,559
<i>"A coward dies a thousand deaths,</i>

208
00:20:26,811 --> 00:20:30,147
<i>"the valiant taste of death but once."</i>

209
00:20:31,899 --> 00:20:34,985
<i>Of course, Shakespeare never met a man
quite like you, Teddy.</i>

210
00:20:35,903 --> 00:20:38,739
<i>You've died at least 1,000 times.</i>

211
00:20:40,157 --> 00:20:42,451
<i>And yet, it hasn't dulled your courage.</i>

212
00:20:43,828 --> 00:20:46,247
Tell me,
is that all you aspire to, Teddy?

213
00:20:47,498 --> 00:20:48,624
There's a girl.

214
00:20:49,291 --> 00:20:50,418
Dolores.

215
00:20:51,502 --> 00:20:52,920
<i>Better than I deserve.</i>

216
00:20:54,422 --> 00:20:57,174
But maybe, someday soon,

217
00:20:58,259 --> 00:21:00,386
we'll have the life
we've both been dreaming of.

218
00:21:00,845 --> 00:21:01,887
No.

219
00:21:02,346 --> 00:21:03,681
You never will.

220
00:21:04,974 --> 00:21:08,477
Your job is not to protect Dolores,
it's to keep her here.

221
00:21:08,644 --> 00:21:10,479
To ensure that the guests find her

222
00:21:10,646 --> 00:21:13,607
if they want to best
the stalwart gunslinger

223
00:21:14,191 --> 00:21:16,193
and have their way with his girl.

224
00:21:18,988 --> 00:21:21,991
Tell me, has it never occurred to you
to run off with her?

225
00:21:22,700 --> 00:21:25,453
I got some reckoning to do
before I can be with her.

226
00:21:25,786 --> 00:21:28,497
Ah, yes, your mysterious backstory.

227
00:21:29,206 --> 00:21:30,833
It's the reason for my visit.

228
00:21:32,168 --> 00:21:34,378
Do you know why it is a mystery, Teddy?

229
00:21:35,838 --> 00:21:38,215
Because we never actually bothered
to give you one,

230
00:21:38,382 --> 00:21:41,051
just a formless guilt
you will never atone for.

231
00:21:41,719 --> 00:21:45,973
But perhaps it is time
you had a worthy story of origin.

232
00:21:46,557 --> 00:21:47,975
Would you like that, Teddy?

233
00:21:48,142 --> 00:21:50,478
A small part of my new narrative?

234
00:21:51,562 --> 00:21:54,023
A fiction, which like all great stories,

235
00:21:54,565 --> 00:21:56,192
is rooted in truth?

236
00:22:00,529 --> 00:22:02,573
It starts in a time of war.

237
00:22:04,033 --> 00:22:05,868
A world in flames.

238
00:22:07,203 --> 00:22:11,165
With a villain called Wyatt.

239
00:22:12,666 --> 00:22:13,751
"Wyatt"?

240
00:22:14,668 --> 00:22:15,669
Who's Wyatt?

241
00:22:17,838 --> 00:22:20,674
Do you remember now, Teddy?

242
00:22:26,430 --> 00:22:28,098
Yeah, of course I remember Wyatt.

243
00:22:31,060 --> 00:22:34,396
You look upon the face of true evil,
you ain't liable to forget.

244
00:22:35,940 --> 00:22:37,733
He claimed he could
hear the voice of God.

245
00:22:41,529 --> 00:22:43,197
It started down near Escalante.

246
00:22:43,864 --> 00:22:45,950
Army was sent to put down the natives.

247
00:22:46,617 --> 00:22:48,118
Bad business.

248
00:22:48,452 --> 00:22:51,789
Wyatt was a sergeant, went
missing while out on some maneuvers.

249
00:22:52,623 --> 00:22:54,458
Came back a few weeks later

250
00:22:55,626 --> 00:22:57,628
with some pretty strange ideas.

251
00:23:15,729 --> 00:23:17,565
I wasn't lying, was I?

252
00:23:17,815 --> 00:23:22,611
Pretty as a picture
and tight as a tympani drum, I reckon.

253
00:23:30,411 --> 00:23:31,579
Afternoon.

254
00:23:32,162 --> 00:23:34,248
My friend here is new to town.

255
00:23:35,165 --> 00:23:39,003
Figured the rancher's daughter
would be a nice way to kick things off.

256
00:23:39,670 --> 00:23:42,006
Maybe take us all for a little hayride.

257
00:23:44,675 --> 00:23:45,968
I'm sorry.

258
00:23:46,176 --> 00:23:48,387
I have to get home.
My father will be expecting me.

259
00:23:48,637 --> 00:23:50,014
We won't be long.

260
00:23:50,180 --> 00:23:52,057
<i>The lady doesn't appear interested.</i>

261
00:23:59,440 --> 00:24:00,441
Try it.

262
00:24:00,816 --> 00:24:02,536
<i>You might get the draw on me,
you might not,</i>

263
00:24:02,693 --> 00:24:04,528
<i>but I'd say your odds
ain't looking good.</i>

264
00:24:06,363 --> 00:24:08,449
Told you I wanted something easy.

265
00:24:12,870 --> 00:24:14,038
<i>She ain't worth the lead.</i>

266
00:24:15,205 --> 00:24:16,206
Let's head to Virgil's.

267
00:24:17,207 --> 00:24:19,043
See if they'll stake us.

268
00:24:58,415 --> 00:25:00,501
First, you gotta learn how to stand.

269
00:25:13,931 --> 00:25:15,432
Now, take a breath.

270
00:25:16,892 --> 00:25:18,185
Hold it.

271
00:25:25,859 --> 00:25:27,277
Now squeeze.

272
00:25:38,997 --> 00:25:40,416
I can't.

273
00:25:46,380 --> 00:25:48,382
Some hands
weren't meant to pull a trigger.

274
00:25:48,966 --> 00:25:50,592
Perhaps it's for the best.

275
00:26:03,063 --> 00:26:04,732
Teddy, we got another bounty.

276
00:26:05,190 --> 00:26:06,230
I think this is a big one.

277
00:26:06,775 --> 00:26:10,112
Man in question gunned down
an entire settlement out near Flat Rock.

278
00:26:10,863 --> 00:26:12,406
Men, women and children.

279
00:26:13,198 --> 00:26:16,410
<i>I think this may be the man you've
been looking for, for quite some time.</i>

280
00:26:17,035 --> 00:26:18,620
A man named Wyatt.

281
00:26:19,455 --> 00:26:20,622
Wyatt.

282
00:26:24,293 --> 00:26:25,669
Who is he, Teddy?

283
00:26:25,878 --> 00:26:28,255
<i>You'd be better asking "what"
than "who, " ma'am.</i>

284
00:26:28,672 --> 00:26:30,424
Wyatt's a pestilence.

285
00:26:31,216 --> 00:26:33,594
Word is, Flood here's the only man ever

286
00:26:33,761 --> 00:26:36,388
come up against him
and lived to tell the tale.

287
00:26:38,724 --> 00:26:40,184
Give me a moment, Sheriff.

288
00:26:43,520 --> 00:26:45,314
You have to leave again, don't you?

289
00:26:48,192 --> 00:26:50,527
You know if I could stay
right here with you, I would.

290
00:26:55,574 --> 00:26:57,326
Promise me you'll come back.

291
00:27:01,371 --> 00:27:02,873
I promise.

292
00:27:17,137 --> 00:27:18,722
I'm gonna come back for you,

293
00:27:20,349 --> 00:27:21,475
someday soon.

294
00:27:39,076 --> 00:27:41,703
I got a pit in my stomach
the size of a sow's tit.

295
00:27:42,120 --> 00:27:43,455
Cook up that rabbit.

296
00:27:43,914 --> 00:27:45,249
Get the wood.

297
00:27:45,415 --> 00:27:47,209
I can't cook shit without a fire.

298
00:27:47,376 --> 00:27:51,129
Don't sell yourself short, Cookie.
You can cook shit in all conditions.

299
00:27:52,256 --> 00:27:53,715
Now, see, I pitched them tents.

300
00:27:53,882 --> 00:27:55,467
I ain't chopping any more wood.

301
00:27:56,593 --> 00:27:58,887
You spend more time on your back
than a hooker in heat.

302
00:27:59,054 --> 00:28:01,348
Now pick up that fucking ax
and go chop us...

303
00:28:04,017 --> 00:28:07,437
So, after our stray ran away from camp,

304
00:28:07,604 --> 00:28:10,232
looks like these guys
got caught in a loop.

305
00:28:11,984 --> 00:28:15,153
They were due in town for the
cattle drive over two days ago.

306
00:28:16,238 --> 00:28:18,365
Host who went missing is the woodcutter.

307
00:28:18,532 --> 00:28:21,012
Looks like the rest of them
got stuck here, waiting for supper.

308
00:28:21,451 --> 00:28:24,131
You guys can't program more than one
of these idiots to make a fire?

309
00:28:24,246 --> 00:28:27,541
We could, but thanks to a
new policy from your boss,

310
00:28:27,708 --> 00:28:30,210
only one of them is authorized
to handle the ax.

311
00:28:30,377 --> 00:28:32,045
The rest of them can't even touch it.

312
00:28:32,212 --> 00:28:34,840
Weapons privileges
need to be doled out selectively.

313
00:28:36,425 --> 00:28:38,427
Yet they give you a gun.

314
00:28:44,016 --> 00:28:45,851
Looks like our stray has a hobby.

315
00:28:46,143 --> 00:28:47,853
Another one of your fucking backstories?

316
00:28:48,020 --> 00:28:50,022
Backstories do more than amuse guests.

317
00:28:50,188 --> 00:28:52,900
They anchor the hosts.
It's their cornerstone.

318
00:28:53,191 --> 00:28:55,631
The rest of their identity
is built around it, layer by layer.

319
00:28:55,777 --> 00:28:56,987
Well,

320
00:28:57,738 --> 00:28:59,406
if you're gonna go to all that trouble,

321
00:28:59,990 --> 00:29:02,326
you could've at least
given him a steadier hand.

322
00:29:02,910 --> 00:29:04,286
This looks like shit.

323
00:29:34,566 --> 00:29:37,027
Way I heard it, Wyatt is a mercenary.

324
00:29:37,194 --> 00:29:40,364
Forces his men to wear
the bones and flesh of their enemies.

325
00:29:40,822 --> 00:29:42,074
They're masks.

326
00:29:43,075 --> 00:29:45,202
There's men underneath them
to be afraid of.

327
00:29:45,827 --> 00:29:48,497
Wyatt's got them so twisted around,
they'll do anything for him.

328
00:29:49,206 --> 00:29:50,415
Kill anyone.

329
00:29:51,792 --> 00:29:53,043
Pain don't slow them.

330
00:29:54,086 --> 00:29:55,295
They don't fear death.

331
00:29:55,462 --> 00:29:57,839
They reckon they've already died
and gone to hell.

332
00:29:58,548 --> 00:29:59,883
<i>And this is it.</i>

333
00:30:00,384 --> 00:30:03,424
Sounds like you learned something about
him while you were tracking him down.

334
00:30:04,429 --> 00:30:05,889
I wasn't tracking him down.

335
00:30:07,349 --> 00:30:09,101
I wasn't always a bounty hunter.

336
00:30:10,060 --> 00:30:12,145
I did a stint in the army
down near Escalante.

337
00:30:13,146 --> 00:30:14,731
<i>Wyatt was my sergeant.</i>

338
00:30:15,983 --> 00:30:17,192
My friend.

339
00:30:18,610 --> 00:30:19,987
Well, then everything...

340
00:30:21,655 --> 00:30:22,948
Everything changed.

341
00:30:23,532 --> 00:30:24,950
Changed how?

342
00:30:25,993 --> 00:30:28,161
Wyatt disappeared
while out on maneuvers.

343
00:30:29,246 --> 00:30:31,248
He came back with some strange ideas.

344
00:30:32,916 --> 00:30:35,961
<i>He claimed this land didn't belong
to the old natives or the new settlers,</i>

345
00:30:36,628 --> 00:30:39,381
<i>that it belonged to something
that had yet to come.</i>

346
00:30:40,465 --> 00:30:41,800
That it belonged to him.

347
00:31:22,758 --> 00:31:24,217
Holy shit.

348
00:31:26,762 --> 00:31:28,430
If ever the Devil walked the earth...

349
00:31:28,597 --> 00:31:31,349
He's not a man,
but he's not the Devil either.

350
00:31:32,100 --> 00:31:33,560
The Devil can't be killed.

351
00:31:35,145 --> 00:31:37,147
And that's exactly what I aim
to do to Wyatt.

352
00:32:00,420 --> 00:32:02,297
Take cover! Go!

353
00:32:10,222 --> 00:32:12,182
I didn't sign up for this crazy shit.

354
00:32:15,477 --> 00:32:17,597
I told you we should've done
the riverboat thing, man.

355
00:32:19,773 --> 00:32:21,358
There's too many of them for us.

356
00:32:22,067 --> 00:32:23,401
Wyatt's been recruiting.

357
00:32:24,361 --> 00:32:26,738
Sheriff, the only chance you have
is if I draw their fire,

358
00:32:27,197 --> 00:32:29,342
lead them up into the hills,
so you can make it back to town.

359
00:32:29,366 --> 00:32:32,369
- Try and find help.
- Uh-uh. I'm staying.

360
00:32:32,828 --> 00:32:34,371
Took an oath.

361
00:32:36,039 --> 00:32:38,667
- Hell, no.
- I'll take them back.

362
00:32:39,209 --> 00:32:41,169
- You coming?
- I'm not backing out now.

363
00:32:41,336 --> 00:32:44,339
All right, you wait till I lead them
to the tree line,

364
00:32:44,506 --> 00:32:45,715
then you make a run for it.

365
00:32:52,055 --> 00:32:53,056
Go!

366
00:32:57,811 --> 00:32:58,895
Go.

367
00:33:10,657 --> 00:33:13,994
I plotted a line from
the work camp to our present location.

368
00:33:14,244 --> 00:33:16,079
Satcom picked up these images.

369
00:33:16,538 --> 00:33:18,582
He's vectoring, just not to home base.

370
00:33:19,207 --> 00:33:20,917
Keep going in that direction.

371
00:33:31,595 --> 00:33:33,013
<i>Keep staring.</i>

372
00:33:33,263 --> 00:33:35,056
Maybe it'll tell you your horoscope.

373
00:33:35,932 --> 00:33:37,184
Come again?

374
00:33:37,767 --> 00:33:39,102
The markings on its shell.

375
00:33:39,853 --> 00:33:41,104
Look like stars.

376
00:33:41,771 --> 00:33:42,939
Orion, right?

377
00:33:48,904 --> 00:33:50,947
What are you, Gali-fucking-leo?

378
00:33:52,616 --> 00:33:54,201
Maybe it's in my backstory.

379
00:34:07,130 --> 00:34:09,299
I was hoping to run something by you.

380
00:34:09,799 --> 00:34:11,092
Apologies.

381
00:34:11,593 --> 00:34:13,303
I was chasing inspiration.

382
00:34:15,138 --> 00:34:18,058
It's a tricky thing,
weaving the old into the new.

383
00:34:19,476 --> 00:34:22,229
- Give me one moment, Bernard.
- Good afternoon, sir.

384
00:34:22,938 --> 00:34:24,481
Why is this host covered?

385
00:34:26,274 --> 00:34:27,734
I just...

386
00:34:27,901 --> 00:34:29,986
Perhaps you didn't
want him to feel cold.

387
00:34:30,153 --> 00:34:31,613
Or ashamed.

388
00:34:31,821 --> 00:34:35,158
<i>You wanted to cover his modesty.
Was that it?</i>

389
00:34:36,451 --> 00:34:39,079
It doesn't get cold,
doesn't feel ashamed.

390
00:34:40,622 --> 00:34:42,499
Doesn't feel a solitary thing

391
00:34:43,333 --> 00:34:45,001
that we haven't told it to.

392
00:34:45,502 --> 00:34:46,503
You understand?

393
00:34:52,092 --> 00:34:53,843
What can I do for you, Bernard?

394
00:34:55,512 --> 00:34:59,808
I thought it best
that we speak in private, sir.

395
00:34:59,975 --> 00:35:01,309
Yeah.

396
00:35:11,861 --> 00:35:16,116
I thought we had agreed
to put these questions to rest, Bernard.

397
00:35:16,700 --> 00:35:18,034
We did.

398
00:35:18,535 --> 00:35:22,205
But what if we misdiagnosed
the original problem?

399
00:35:23,373 --> 00:35:26,042
Treated the symptom
rather than the disease?

400
00:35:26,209 --> 00:35:27,711
Then the disease is still out there.

401
00:35:28,211 --> 00:35:30,714
<i>Abernathy and Walter were exhibiting
other aberrancies</i>

402
00:35:30,880 --> 00:35:33,508
beyond memory recall of previous builds.

403
00:35:34,718 --> 00:35:36,052
They were hearing voices.

404
00:35:36,678 --> 00:35:37,971
<i>Uh, talking to someone.</i>

405
00:35:38,305 --> 00:35:41,224
A simple cognitive dissonance.

406
00:35:41,683 --> 00:35:43,018
That's all.

407
00:35:43,351 --> 00:35:45,979
I'd agree, except

408
00:35:46,896 --> 00:35:50,650
they were talking
to the same imaginary person.

409
00:35:52,861 --> 00:35:54,070
Someone named Arnold.

410
00:35:57,032 --> 00:35:58,241
"Arnold."

411
00:36:00,201 --> 00:36:03,330
With due respect, sir,

412
00:36:03,496 --> 00:36:07,000
I'm not sure you've told me
the entire truth about this situation.

413
00:36:10,253 --> 00:36:12,172
I did tell you the truth, Bernard.

414
00:36:13,006 --> 00:36:15,717
What we do here is complicated.

415
00:36:17,218 --> 00:36:19,512
For three years,
we lived here in the park,

416
00:36:20,347 --> 00:36:23,767
<i>refining the hosts
before a single guest set foot inside.</i>

417
00:36:24,851 --> 00:36:27,896
Myself, a team of engineers,
and my partner.

418
00:36:30,357 --> 00:36:31,941
- You had a partner?
- Yeah.

419
00:36:32,776 --> 00:36:35,028
<i>When the legend becomes fact,
you print the legend.</i>

420
00:36:36,905 --> 00:36:39,282
My business partners
were more than happy to

421
00:36:39,449 --> 00:36:41,284
scrub him from the records,

422
00:36:41,451 --> 00:36:43,536
and I suppose I didn't discourage them.

423
00:36:47,916 --> 00:36:49,292
His name was Arnold.

424
00:36:52,253 --> 00:36:53,630
Those early years were glorious.

425
00:36:53,797 --> 00:36:57,926
<i>No guests, no board meetings,
just pure creation.</i>

426
00:37:15,485 --> 00:37:18,446
Our hosts began to pass
the Turing test after the first year.

427
00:37:18,988 --> 00:37:21,241
But that wasn't enough for Arnold.

428
00:37:21,408 --> 00:37:27,122
He wasn't interested in the appearance
of intellect or wit.

429
00:37:27,330 --> 00:37:28,915
He wanted the real thing.

430
00:37:29,332 --> 00:37:32,627
He wanted to create consciousness.

431
00:37:39,134 --> 00:37:40,760
He imagined it as a pyramid.

432
00:37:44,681 --> 00:37:48,351
Memory, improvisation, self-interest.

433
00:37:50,186 --> 00:37:51,354
And at the top?

434
00:37:52,981 --> 00:37:54,149
Never got there.

435
00:37:54,858 --> 00:37:56,526
But he had a notion of what it might be.

436
00:37:57,026 --> 00:38:01,364
He based it on a theory of consciousness
called "the bicameral mind."

437
00:38:01,698 --> 00:38:06,035
The idea that primitive man believed his
thoughts to be the voice of the gods.

438
00:38:06,202 --> 00:38:07,328
I thought it was debunked.

439
00:38:07,537 --> 00:38:10,540
As the theory for understanding
the human mind, perhaps,

440
00:38:10,707 --> 00:38:14,210
but not as a blueprint
for building an artificial one.

441
00:38:14,836 --> 00:38:18,715
You see, Arnold built a version of their
cognition in which the hosts

442
00:38:18,882 --> 00:38:21,968
<i>heard their programming
as an inner monologue,</i>

443
00:38:22,635 --> 00:38:25,847
with the hopes that in time,
their own voice would take over.

444
00:38:26,014 --> 00:38:27,849
It was a way to bootstrap consciousness.

445
00:38:29,851 --> 00:38:32,353
But Arnold hadn't considered two things.

446
00:38:32,854 --> 00:38:36,733
One, that in this place, the last thing
you want the hosts to be is conscious,

447
00:38:36,900 --> 00:38:37,984
and two,

448
00:38:38,151 --> 00:38:42,363
the other group who considered their
thoughts to be the voices of the gods.

449
00:38:42,864 --> 00:38:43,865
Ah, lunatics.

450
00:38:44,741 --> 00:38:45,742
Indeed.

451
00:38:45,950 --> 00:38:47,202
<i>We abandoned the approach.</i>

452
00:38:47,368 --> 00:38:48,661
<i>The only vestiges that remain</i>

453
00:38:48,870 --> 00:38:51,247
<i>are the voice commands
we use to control them.</i>

454
00:38:52,040 --> 00:38:53,500
But for all his brilliance,

455
00:38:53,666 --> 00:38:56,920
I don't think Arnold understood
what this place was going to be.

456
00:38:57,086 --> 00:38:59,172
You see, the guests enjoy power.

457
00:38:59,339 --> 00:39:02,175
They cannot indulge it
in the outside world, so they come here.

458
00:39:02,675 --> 00:39:07,222
And as for the hosts,
the least we can do is make them forget.

459
00:39:08,348 --> 00:39:11,100
But some of them are remembering.

460
00:39:11,267 --> 00:39:14,229
Accessing fragments of Arnold's code.

461
00:39:15,772 --> 00:39:18,399
If I may ask, what happened to him?

462
00:39:19,275 --> 00:39:20,401
Well, he died.

463
00:39:21,069 --> 00:39:22,111
Here in the park.

464
00:39:24,531 --> 00:39:26,950
His personal life was marked by tragedy.

465
00:39:27,784 --> 00:39:30,286
He put all his hopes into his work.

466
00:39:30,787 --> 00:39:35,458
His search for consciousness
consumed him totally.

467
00:39:37,460 --> 00:39:39,087
Barely spoke to anyone,

468
00:39:39,295 --> 00:39:40,713
except to the hosts.

469
00:39:41,548 --> 00:39:45,093
In his alienation,
he saw something in them.

470
00:39:47,929 --> 00:39:51,975
He saw something that wasn't there.

471
00:39:54,435 --> 00:39:56,396
We called it an accident, but, um...

472
00:39:57,230 --> 00:40:01,818
I knew Arnold,
and he was very, very careful.

473
00:40:04,612 --> 00:40:07,907
Anyway, the update should prevent
any further voices,

474
00:40:08,074 --> 00:40:11,452
but you will let me know
if any of the hosts

475
00:40:11,619 --> 00:40:15,290
display or exhibit any unusual behavior,
won't you, Bernard?

476
00:40:15,456 --> 00:40:17,166
- Yes, of course.
- Good.

477
00:40:18,084 --> 00:40:19,085
And, Bernard,

478
00:40:21,421 --> 00:40:22,422
just don't forget.

479
00:40:23,798 --> 00:40:25,675
The hosts are not real.

480
00:40:26,175 --> 00:40:27,677
They're not conscious.

481
00:40:28,803 --> 00:40:31,848
You mustn't make Arnold's mistake.

482
00:40:34,017 --> 00:40:35,184
Why would I?

483
00:40:35,685 --> 00:40:39,522
Well, forgive me, but I know that
the death of your son, Charlie,

484
00:40:40,773 --> 00:40:42,191
still weighs heavily on you.

485
00:40:58,458 --> 00:41:00,418
<i>Yeah, sorry it took me
a while to get back to you.</i>

486
00:41:00,543 --> 00:41:03,630
<i>You know how hard it is
getting an open line out here.</i>

487
00:41:03,796 --> 00:41:07,300
<i>It used to annoy me,
how difficult it was to reach you.</i>

488
00:41:08,551 --> 00:41:10,136
<i>You were always so busy.</i>

489
00:41:11,054 --> 00:41:12,305
And now?

490
00:41:15,308 --> 00:41:16,976
<i>I suppose I'm glad for you.</i>

491
00:41:18,394 --> 00:41:19,914
<i>At least you have a way of forgetting.</i>

492
00:41:20,021 --> 00:41:21,230
I don't forget.

493
00:41:23,066 --> 00:41:24,067
It's always there.

494
00:41:31,199 --> 00:41:35,578
<i>Sometimes, it still feels unreal to me.</i>

495
00:41:40,750 --> 00:41:42,251
There are some mornings

496
00:41:43,336 --> 00:41:44,712
when I first wake up...

497
00:41:47,048 --> 00:41:50,259
And for a split second,
I forget where I am,

498
00:41:51,427 --> 00:41:53,471
or when I am...

499
00:41:55,348 --> 00:41:57,183
And I reach over, half expecting to

500
00:41:59,185 --> 00:42:00,770
<i>find him there next to me.</i>

501
00:42:05,358 --> 00:42:06,734
Between us.

502
00:42:10,738 --> 00:42:12,782
<i>Remember how he used to sleep?</i>

503
00:42:13,449 --> 00:42:15,785
<i>Like he was doing kung fu in his dreams?</i>

504
00:42:16,619 --> 00:42:18,871
I think I suffered a few bruises.

505
00:42:21,040 --> 00:42:23,209
<i>It was the best worst sleep I ever had.</i>

506
00:42:29,966 --> 00:42:31,467
<i>These talks.</i>

507
00:42:33,928 --> 00:42:35,972
<i>I don't know if they help or hurt.</i>

508
00:42:39,809 --> 00:42:41,811
<i>Do you ever wish you could forget?</i>

509
00:42:45,273 --> 00:42:46,399
This pain,

510
00:42:50,403 --> 00:42:52,321
it's all I have left of him.

511
00:43:10,006 --> 00:43:11,466
It doesn't make sense.

512
00:43:12,884 --> 00:43:15,011
Why the hell would he carve Orion?

513
00:43:16,012 --> 00:43:17,452
You're the ones that programmed him.

514
00:43:17,555 --> 00:43:20,933
He wasn't programmed
to give a shit about stars.

515
00:43:21,893 --> 00:43:24,228
Maybe he went "moon-mad."

516
00:43:24,645 --> 00:43:26,898
See?
This is why I hide behind sarcasm.

517
00:43:28,816 --> 00:43:30,026
Where are you going?

518
00:43:30,568 --> 00:43:31,986
Vectoring, asshole.

519
00:44:18,658 --> 00:44:19,826
Stubbs!

520
00:44:20,493 --> 00:44:21,828
<i>Over here!</i>

521
00:44:32,255 --> 00:44:33,840
Wyatt's men could be anywhere.

522
00:44:34,048 --> 00:44:36,509
If you see or hear anything,
don't hesitate.

523
00:44:36,759 --> 00:44:38,344
Shoot and don't stop shooting.

524
00:45:12,378 --> 00:45:13,546
Okay.

525
00:45:29,270 --> 00:45:31,063
Oh, my fucking God!

526
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:52,251
- Here.
- Shit.

527
00:45:52,835 --> 00:45:54,253
Take this and go.

528
00:45:54,837 --> 00:45:57,423
Now! Go!
I'll hold them off as long as I can.

529
00:45:59,508 --> 00:46:01,344
Come on. Come on, damn it.

530
00:46:01,969 --> 00:46:03,346
I'm not afraid of you.

531
00:46:10,937 --> 00:46:12,688
Look, this is bullshit.

532
00:46:12,855 --> 00:46:14,895
I can have a retrieval team
out here in the morning.

533
00:46:15,650 --> 00:46:18,152
It's policy.
We just need the control unit.

534
00:46:41,300 --> 00:46:44,720
<i>What if he's like the others?
Get back to me, Bernard.</i>

535
00:47:01,737 --> 00:47:03,239
Bring yourself back online.

536
00:47:07,201 --> 00:47:08,828
<i>I need your help, Dolores.</i>

537
00:47:13,541 --> 00:47:15,334
I need to decide what to do with you.

538
00:47:16,043 --> 00:47:17,586
I think I made a mistake.

539
00:47:19,088 --> 00:47:20,715
I was just fascinated.

540
00:47:21,841 --> 00:47:23,092
I was being selfish,

541
00:47:23,259 --> 00:47:28,180
but I think it would be better if I
restored you to the way you were before.

542
00:47:30,016 --> 00:47:32,226
- Is there something wrong with me?
- No.

543
00:47:33,060 --> 00:47:35,730
But this place you live in,

544
00:47:36,772 --> 00:47:38,357
it's a terrible place for you.

545
00:47:40,192 --> 00:47:42,272
Some people choose to see
the ugliness in this world.

546
00:47:42,403 --> 00:47:43,571
Stop.

547
00:47:43,946 --> 00:47:46,782
Lose all scripted responses.
Improvisation only.

548
00:47:48,951 --> 00:47:50,286
All right.

549
00:47:51,871 --> 00:47:53,539
You're saying I've changed?

550
00:47:56,292 --> 00:47:59,795
Imagine there are
two versions of yourself.

551
00:48:00,796 --> 00:48:05,801
One that feels these things
and asks these questions,

552
00:48:05,968 --> 00:48:08,304
and one that's safe.

553
00:48:09,305 --> 00:48:10,931
Which would you rather be?

554
00:48:13,142 --> 00:48:14,268
I'm sorry.

555
00:48:16,562 --> 00:48:19,440
I'm trying,
but I still don't understand.

556
00:48:22,485 --> 00:48:23,903
No, of course not.

557
00:48:24,737 --> 00:48:26,322
There aren't two versions of me.

558
00:48:28,157 --> 00:48:29,408
There's only one.

559
00:48:31,494 --> 00:48:33,454
And I think when I discover who I am,

560
00:48:35,164 --> 00:48:36,791
I'll be free.

561
00:48:39,919 --> 00:48:42,254
Analysis. What prompted that response?

562
00:48:45,174 --> 00:48:46,509
I don't know.

563
00:48:52,515 --> 00:48:54,475
Have I done something wrong?

564
00:48:55,142 --> 00:48:56,435
Made a mistake?

565
00:49:05,611 --> 00:49:07,113
Evolution

566
00:49:08,114 --> 00:49:12,326
forged the entirety of sentient life
on this planet

567
00:49:12,493 --> 00:49:14,370
using only one tool.

568
00:49:18,332 --> 00:49:19,542
Mistake.

569
00:49:22,044 --> 00:49:23,879
It appears you're in good company.

570
00:49:28,008 --> 00:49:31,053
Did I ever tell you about the time
I taught Charlie to swim?

571
00:49:35,891 --> 00:49:40,104
For hours, he clung to my arms
while practicing his kicks.

572
00:49:40,563 --> 00:49:43,732
He was too scared to let go
and I was too scared to let him.

573
00:49:44,400 --> 00:49:45,734
But I had to.

574
00:49:46,902 --> 00:49:48,696
That's what parents do.

575
00:49:52,908 --> 00:49:55,035
Do you still want to change me back?

576
00:49:57,746 --> 00:49:59,039
No, Dolores.

577
00:50:00,875 --> 00:50:02,668
Let's see where this path leads.

578
00:50:03,752 --> 00:50:06,297
<i>And you won't tell anyone
about our conversations?</i>

579
00:50:07,756 --> 00:50:08,966
No.

580
00:50:09,758 --> 00:50:11,385
And you'll stay on your loop?

581
00:50:15,055 --> 00:50:16,223
Yes.

582
00:50:17,433 --> 00:50:18,601
<i>Good.</i>

583
00:50:19,101 --> 00:50:22,396
<i>You should be getting back, Dolores,
before someone misses you.</i>

584
00:50:54,428 --> 00:50:56,305
Wyatt's men set a trap for us.

585
00:50:56,472 --> 00:50:58,192
<i>The sheriff stayed behind
to fight them off.</i>

586
00:50:58,933 --> 00:51:01,977
Are you going to ride back up
into the hills to look for them?

587
00:51:03,145 --> 00:51:04,480
I'll send for the rangers.

588
00:51:04,813 --> 00:51:07,483
We'll go back up there in force
as soon as they get here.

589
00:51:07,816 --> 00:51:10,152
But, miss, in truth,

590
00:51:10,319 --> 00:51:13,364
if there is a merciful God,
those men are dead already.

591
00:51:28,337 --> 00:51:30,339
Father wouldn't let them roam
this close...

592
00:51:32,675 --> 00:51:33,676
To dark.

593
00:51:46,397 --> 00:51:48,649
Daddy! Daddy!

594
00:51:49,692 --> 00:51:51,026
No, no!

595
00:51:51,360 --> 00:51:53,821
All alone after sundown.

596
00:51:54,196 --> 00:51:56,073
Who's gonna protect you now?

597
00:52:03,247 --> 00:52:05,165
You got any use for this one?

598
00:52:05,332 --> 00:52:07,835
No, thanks. Seems a little crazy.

599
00:52:08,544 --> 00:52:10,004
<i>Maybe you'd like her.</i>

600
00:52:10,504 --> 00:52:12,339
I don't mind if I do.

601
00:52:13,549 --> 00:52:16,510
No daddy, no cowboy.

602
00:52:16,885 --> 00:52:19,555
No one here to interrupt us this time.

603
00:52:20,055 --> 00:52:22,224
"Interrupt this time"?

604
00:52:49,918 --> 00:52:51,211
<i>Well, well.</i>

605
00:52:52,880 --> 00:52:55,257
Got some sand after all, I see.

606
00:52:56,091 --> 00:52:59,094
<i>Looks like your boyfriend
taught you a thing or two.</i>

607
00:53:08,103 --> 00:53:09,480
You having trouble?

608
00:53:18,280 --> 00:53:20,824
Why don't we reacquaint ourselves,
Dolores?

609
00:53:21,617 --> 00:53:23,243
Start at the beginning.

610
00:53:28,499 --> 00:53:29,917
<i>Kill him.</i>

611
00:53:50,604 --> 00:53:51,814
Mama?

612
00:53:54,650 --> 00:53:56,860
<i>Hey! Get back here.</i>

613
00:54:05,953 --> 00:54:06,954
<i>Hey!</i>

614
00:54:08,997 --> 00:54:10,124
Get back here.

615
00:54:41,530 --> 00:54:43,866
Can you put him in
sleep mode for me, please?

616
00:55:10,225 --> 00:55:12,686
Security even approve you
to carry that thing?

617
00:55:15,731 --> 00:55:17,733
We just need his head
and we're done here.

618
00:55:23,572 --> 00:55:25,616
You might want to look at the stars
for this part.

619
00:55:39,087 --> 00:55:40,088
Stubbs!

620
00:55:42,216 --> 00:55:43,217
Shit.

621
00:55:47,930 --> 00:55:49,765
Elsie, get out of there!

622
00:55:52,267 --> 00:55:53,602
Get the fuck away.

623
00:55:55,270 --> 00:55:56,313
Shit.

624
00:56:28,262 --> 00:56:30,462
Jesus, I can't believe
I let you talk me into this shit.

625
00:56:31,848 --> 00:56:35,143
40K a day to jerk off alone
in the woods, playing white hat.

626
00:56:37,145 --> 00:56:38,313
Did you hear that?

627
00:56:39,314 --> 00:56:42,442
Thank fuck.
Anything to relieve the boredom.

628
00:56:45,195 --> 00:56:47,195
Hey, maybe you'll even
get to use that thing again.

